INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3080_L012_v21$$, 2027, $$This Budget Line Item (BLI) was consolidated for the FY27 President's Budget (PB). The exhibit includes funding from BLIs 821800, 822230, 822910, 822990, 823230, 823990, 824010, 825990, 826210, 826990.
 The new BLI, 827000, improves transparency, execution, and long-term planning.

 BLI 827000 funds procurement of Tactical and non-Tactical vehicles used to support multiple functions and missions at all levels of the Air Force. Without the procurement of these vehicles, the Air Force will not
 have the ability to support the broad spectrum of Air Force operations.

 - Passenger Carrying Vehicles (PCV) include the procurement of sedans, law enforcement sedans, ambulances, armored sedans, small buses, transit buses, large buses, intra-city motorcoaches, and work
 buses. These vehicles are general in nature, but they fulfill unique and distinct needs commensurate with their design. Specific uses for Passenger Carrying Vehicles include, but are not limited to, sedans used
 by the Office of Special Investigations (OSI); law enforcement sedans used by security forces personnel for emergency response, traffic control, patrol duties, and base security operations; ambulances used
 for the movement of patients under field conditions, aircraft crash rescue operations, and routine transportation of patients to and from medical facilities; and buses used to support Air Education and Training
 Command (AETC) training units, Air Force band organizations, protocol offices, and several other missions.

 - Medium Tactical Vehicles (MTV) include a broad class of medium and heavy military specification vehicles with the capability to operate in austere and adverse terrain. They include, but are not limited to Cargo
 Trucks, Wreckers, Dump Trucks, Tractors, Mobilizers, and Medium and Heavy Tactical Trailers. They provide a range of capabilities such as line haul, mobility, resupply, maintenance, recovery, construction and
 civil engineering support. They can be ordered with armor and winch systems. These tactical vehicles are used by Combat Communication Units, Air Support Operations Squadrons (ASOS), Explosive Ordinance
 Disposal units (EOD), and other direct mission support units throughout the Air Force.

 - Civil Air Patrol (CAP) vehicle procurements support the Civil Air Patrol—a Congressionally chartered non‑profit corporation that serves as the Auxiliary of the Air Force—in executing emergency and
 non‑emergency public‑purpose missions for the Department of War and federal, state, local, and non‑governmental authorities. CAP maintains a fleet of approximately 1,060 vehicles supporting 58,000
 volunteers, including ground teams that provide critical communications, search and rescue support for 90 percent of Air Force SAR missions under the National Search and Rescue Plan, disaster relief
 operations, and humanitarian assistance. Vehicles also enable transportation and program execution for more than 26,000 cadets participating in Aerospace Education and Cadet Program activities authorized
 under 36 U.S.C. &#167;403 and 10 U.S.C. &#167;9442. Forty‑two percent of CAP's fleet exceeds the average Air Force vehicle age, and vehicle procurement costs have increased nearly 200 percent since
 CAP's baseline was established in 2006. Vehicle types and quantities may vary in the year of execution due to market availability, cost fluctuations, mission requirements, and organizational needs. CAP
 procurements are executed under Department of War Grant and Agreement Regulations (DoWGARs); standard Air Force central procurement processes do not apply.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Air Force                                                                                                                   Date: April 2026
