INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3080_L020$$, 2026, $$Air Traffic Control and Landing Systems (ATCALS) centrally manages the Air Force's Air Traffic Control (ATC) capability to ensure ATC facilities/equipment can safely and expeditiously support enroute and
 terminal operations in benign and combat areas of responsibility. Major ATCALS systems include, but are not limited to, fixed-base and tactical radars, navigation aids (NAVAIDS), voice communication switches/
 radios, and data processing/automation systems.

 These systems enable air traffic controllers to provide advisory, sequencing, separation, and landing guidance services to all aircraft in assigned airspace. ATCALS must also be inter-operable with systems
 operated by other services, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA), or host nations. When possible, contracts with other services or the FAA are used.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), this item is necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 Current acquisitions include:

 1. DIGITAL ATC RADIO REPLACEMENT: The ATC ground-to-air Very High Frequency (VHF) and Ultra High Frequency (UHF) radios are 30 years old and difficult to maintain. The digital ATC Radio
 Replacement Program replaces ATC fixed-base (FB) and mobile ATC tower radios with state-of-the-art systems and 8.33 kHz channel spacing (reduces frequency interference at highly congested airspace).
 Digital ATC Radios are procured through an FAA, 10-year, fixed-price, base-production contract with two additional re-negotiated option years.

 2. DEPLOYABLE INSTRUMENT LANDING SYSTEM (D-ILS): D-ILS is a Category I Instrument Landing System (200ft decision height/2400ft runway visual range) with remote monitoring and maintenance
 capabilities. D-ILS provides precision approach capability in adverse weather conditions to support tactical military operations, humanitarian assistance /disaster relief efforts, and interoperability with the Civil
 Reserve Air Fleet. The last of 19 operational production units was delivered in Sept 2022. FY 2024 funds complete depot standup.

 3. DEPLOYABLE RADAR APPROACH CONTROL SYSTEM (D-RAPCON)/LIGHTWEIGHT DEPLOYABLE GROUND CONTROLLED APPROACH (LD-GCA): This program refurbishes two Army Air Traffic
 Navigation, Integration, and Coordination System (ATNAVICS). These ATNAVICS provide, terminal area, ATC radar surveillance and communications during adverse weather and night conditions.$$, NULL, $${"bucket":"fy26_specific_pb_v43","method":"direct_li_with_title_overlap","rapidfuzz_score":100.0,"src_li":20,"src_title":"Air Traffic Control & Landing Sys","supersedes":"fy26_pointing_at_fy27_pb_placeholder","applied_at":"2026-05-09T_v196b"}$$, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Air Force Other Procurement.pdf$$, 163, 163, $$f1746a55c0d9f2d4$$, $$2026-05-10T02:12:16.956197+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3080_L021$$, 2026, $$PE 0305137F NATIONAL AIRSPACE SYSTEM (NAS)

 The NAS program modernizes and sustains the Department of Defense (DoD) Air Traffic Control (ATC) system in concert with the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). NAS increases safety of flight, provides
 systems and facilities interoperable with FAA, replaces aging DoD ATC systems, provides identical service to military and civilian aircraft, and reduces DoD flight cancellations/delays and maintenance.

 NAS includes two programs: the ATC Voice Recorder Replacement (VRR) and the ATC Voice Switch Replacement (VSR). The Time Division Multi-Plexing to Internet Protocol (TDM to IP) migration program was
 started in FY 2024 with program support funds ($399 thousand); however, the program is now being funded with Operations and Maintenance funds as unit cost is less than $300 thousand and is not centrally
 managed. The TDM to IP migration program description is provided below for information only.

 The ATC VRR replaces end-of-life Digital Audio Legal Recorder (DALR) that is no longer supported by the original equipment manufacturer. Recording of ATC controller-to-pilot and ATC tower communications
 is required to support accident investigations, near misses, runway incursions, etc. Voice are in all Air Force ATC towers/Radar Approach Control (RAPCON) facilities. Replacement recorders are being procured
 though a Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) fixed-price contract with production options through FY 2030. The FAA will also be the lead agency for Operational Safety, Suitability and Effectiveness (OSS&E)
 and lifecycle support. An estimated 160 ATC VRRs will be procured through FY 2024-2030.

 The ATC VSR replaces the 25+ year old Enhanced Terminal Voice Switch (ETVS) systems which provide analog radio and telephone voice communications for ATC voice communications. These legacy, analog
 systems are experiencing multiple support issues and part constraints and do not meet the Department of Defense (DoD) Chief Information Officer (CIO) mandated transition to digital Internet Protocol (IP)
 capability. ATC controller-to-pilot communications are the heart of ATC capability and critical to safety of flight in the airfield terminal area. The FAA is also replacing the same legacy ETVS voice switches and
 joint acquisition strategy is being developed to procure up to 150 ATC VSRs beginning in FY 2026.

 The TDM to IP Migration is a DoD (CIO) mandate and aligned with Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) guidance. TDM to IP migration addresses telecommunications carrier movement from point-
 to-point connections to network connections. USAF ATC utilizes these DISA-approved transport layers for DoD-to-DoD data transfer as well as connection to the overall NAS via the FAA Telecommunications
 Infrastructure (FTI).$$, NULL, $${"bucket":"fy26_specific_pb_v43","method":"direct_li_with_title_overlap","rapidfuzz_score":100.0,"src_li":21,"src_title":"National Airspace System","supersedes":"fy26_pointing_at_fy27_pb_placeholder","applied_at":"2026-05-09T_v196b"}$$, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Air Force Other Procurement.pdf$$, 199, 199, $$3cc537767eb95f11$$, $$2026-05-10T02:12:16.956197+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3080_L021$$, 2027, $$PE 0305137F NATIONAL AIRSPACE SYSTEM (NAS)

 The NAS program modernizes and sustains the Department of War (DoW) Air Traffic Control (ATC) system in concert with the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). NAS increases safety of flight, provides
 systems and facilities interoperable with FAA, replaces aging DoW ATC systems, provides identical service to military and civilian aircraft, and reduces DoW flight cancellations/delays and maintenance.

 NAS includes two programs: the ATC Voice Recorder Replacement (VRR) and the ATC Voice Switch Replacement (VSR).

 The ATC VRR replaces end-of-life Digital Audio Legal Recorder (DALR) that is no longer supported by the original equipment manufacturer. Recording of ATC controller-to-pilot and ATC tower communications
 is required to support accident investigations, near misses, runway incursions, etc. VRRs are in all Air Force ATC towers/Radar Approach Control (RAPCON) facilities. Replacement recorders are being procured
 though a Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) fixed-price contract with production options through FY 2030. The FAA will also be the lead agency for Operational Safety, Suitability and Effectiveness (OSS&E)
 and lifecycle support. An estimated 160 ATC VRRs will be procured through FY 2024-2030.

 The ATC VSR replaces the 25+ year old Enhanced Terminal Voice Switch (ETVS) systems which provide analog radio and telephone voice communications for ATC voice communications. These legacy, analog
 systems are experiencing multiple support issues and part constraints and do not meet the Department of War (DoW) Chief Information Officer (CIO) mandated transition to digital Internet Protocol (IP) capability.
 ATC controller-to-pilot communications are the heart of ATC capability and critical to safety of flight in the airfield terminal area. The FAA is also replacing ETVS voice switches and has awarded two contracts
 under their Brand New Air Traffic Control System program. These contracts to not include options for DoW. To ensure commonality and logistics support with the FAA, the Air Force will procure FAA certified
 ETVS replacement systems with the FAA vendors on separate contracts. A total of 150 VSRs are required.

 In accordance with Section 1815 of the FY 2008 National Defense Authorization Act (P.L. 110-181), these items are necessary for use by the active and reserve components of the Armed Forces for homeland
 defense missions, domestic emergency responses, and providing military support to civil authorities.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in Program Element (PE) 0305137FRRs$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Air Force                                                                                                                Date: April 2026
