 Description:
 The Minimum Essential Emergency Communications Network (MEECN) portfolio modernizes the systems necessary to effectively provide assured communications connectivity between the President and the
 strategic deterrence forces in stressed environments.

 FY27 funding increase supports multiple New Start programs and transfers to satisfy NC3 Upgrades. Programs described below detail the efforts and justify the increase in fund from FY26 to FY27 and include
 MMP Service Life Extension Program, Cyber Implementation Pilot (CIP), FAB-T Command Post Terminals (CPT), Presidential & National Voice Conferencing (PNVC) Integrator.

 The legacy Minuteman Minimum Essential Emergency Communications Network (MEECN) Program (MMP) provides the only survivable, secure, protected, and jam-resistant communications link to ensure the
 President can direct ICBM nuclear forces during all phases of a nuclear conflict. The MMP Service Life Extension Program (SLEP) is critical to ensure MMP stays functional until the follow-on system can be
 fielded. This happens though the replacement of inadequate and unsustainable strategic Extremely High Frequency (EHF) and Very Low Frequency (VLF) communications equipment as well as ensuring the
 spares availability issue is resolved. SLEP will ensure MMP interfaces and communicates with all newly fielded Nuclear Command, Control, and Communications (NC3) systems throughout the Department of
 War (DoW).

 The Cyber Instrumentation Pilot (CIP) suite of solutions provides in-depth situational awareness of NC3 operational health, performance, and cybersecurity posture. It also provides enhanced monitoring that
 will enable proactive identification and mitigation of system degradations and cyber threats, ensuring continuous, reliable, and secure operation of the nation's nuclear deterrent. Procurement enables the
 implementation and installation of Sensor Kits a critical effort to instrument and analyze key cyber terrain within the NC3 architecture, expanding existing cyberspace awareness on DoW networks and systems.

 The Family of Advanced Beyond Line-of-Sight Terminals (FAB-T) Command Post Terminals (CPT) program replaces legacy Milstar terminals and will provide Extremely High Frequency (EHF), protected high
 data rate communication for nuclear and conventional forces to include Presidential and National Voice Conferencing (PNVC).

 FY 2027 transfer of FAB-T CPT and PNVC programs from Space Force (PE 1203001SF / Weapon System Code (WSC) FBLOST / Appropriation 3022 / Procurement Space Force (PSF)) to Air Force (Program
 Element (PE 0303131F)) / WSC 834210 / Appropriation 3080 / Other Procurement (OPAF), Transfer Memo signed 18 Dec 2025.

 FAB-T CPT provides a new, highly secure, state-of-the-art capability for Department of War (DoW) platforms to include strategic platforms and airborne/ground command posts via Milstar, Advanced EHF
 (AEHF), and Evolved Strategic SATCOM (ESS) satellite constellations. FAB-T CPTs will also support the critical command and control (C2) of the Milstar, AEHF, and ESS satellite constellations. In June 2014,


