INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3080_L052$$, 2027, $$JOINT COMMUNICATION SUPPORT ELEMENT (JCSE): Aligned under Joint Enabling Capabilities Command (JECC), US Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM) - is the Department of War's sole joint
 communications unit dedicated to supporting All-Domain Forces. A crisis response organization, JCSE develops technical solutions for modern military communications challenges. Its Modernization Program,
 provides life-cycle recapitalization of essential mission equipment. Authorized by the Director, Joint Staff, this unique program has enabled JCSE to modernize tactical Command, Control, Communications,
 Computers and Intelligence (C4I) systems with emerging technologies. This program is the key enabler that allows JCSE the mission flexibility to rapidly purchase, integrate, and field government and commercial
 off-the-shelf equipment to evolve and provide technical solutions to overcome tactical communication gaps.

 The Modernization Program, a non-program-of-record, provides JCSE the agility to procure cutting-edge technologies, adapt them for military use, and maintain a technological advantage. To ensure relevance
 and effectiveness, the Joint Enabling Capabilities Command (JECC) conducts program reviews with Combatant Commanders and Military Departments twice a year. These reviews serve multiple purposes:
 informing the joint force about emerging capabilities and their alignment with operational requirements; updating Military Departments on progress, and keeping the communication and innovation communities
 abreast of JCSE projects to encourage collaboration and unified solutions. Monthly procurement status reports are submitted to United States Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM), the organization
 tasked with overall responsibility of the JCSE Modernization Program. This comparatively small investment delivers substantial value to the Department of War by enabling JCSE to quickly validate concepts
 and technologies for joint warfighters, fill service capability gaps, and provide effective crisis support. JCSE is a vital component of numerous major contingency plans, including Homeland Defense and those
 addressing National Defense priorities. Moreover, JCSE maintains a comprehensive 24/7 reachback capability via its Global Enterprise Network, managed through its Global Network Operations Center (GNOC),
 providing access to a wide array of DOW and commercial networks.

 In FY2027, there is a budget neutral consolidation of Service JCSE funding into 835110. This is a budget neutral consolidation, not new spending: The $10 million increase in the Air Force's budget is a direct
 transfer of funds previously programmed by the Army and Navy. This is a zero-sum change for the Department of War, not an increase in overall spending.

 This consolidation is the result of a collaborative effort between USTRANSCOM, the Army, the Navy, and the Air Force to improve a vital joint capability. The Services are not withdrawing from the program; they
 are simply streamlining its management. Consolidating the procurement funding under a single service—the Air Force—streamlines program oversight, reduces administrative overhead, and allows for more
 efficient use of taxpayer dollars.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in PE 0207422F, Deployable Command Control and Communications Systems.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Air Force                                                                                                                Date: April 2026
